[{"id":"VH992144","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH947510.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">According to the speaker, the actions of the “man who bought the house” in lines 13-16 are driven by</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH992144_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<p class=\"lead_in\"><span class=\"compose_cluster_phrase type:ordinal\"></span> Read the following poem carefully before you choose your answers.</p>\n\n<p class=\"introduction passage-intro\">This poem is from a collection of poetry published in 2009.</p>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"poetry style:1\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\">Two Trees</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"verse\"><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">1&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>One morning, Don Miguel got out of bed</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>with one idea rooted in his head:</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>to graft his orange to his lemon tree.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>It took him the whole day to work them free,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">5&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>lay open their sides, and lash them tight.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>For twelve months, from the shame or from the fright</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>they put forth nothing; but one day there appeared</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>two lights in the dark leaves. Over the years</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>the limbs would get themselves so tangled up</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">10&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>each bough looked like it gave a double crop,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>and not one kid in the village didn’t know</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>the magic tree in Miguel’s patio.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"verse\"><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>The man who bought the house had had no dream</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>so who can say what dark malicious whim</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">15&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>led him to take his axe and split the bole<span class=\"footnote\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"footnote_mark\">*</span><span class=\"footnote_text\">tree trunk</span></span></span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>along its fused seam, then dig two holes.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>And no, they did not die from solitude;</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>nor did their branches bear a sterile fruit;</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>nor did their unhealed flanks weep every spring</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">20&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>for those four yards that lost them everything,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>as each strained on its shackled root to face</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>the other’s empty, intricate embrace.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>They were trees, and trees don’t weep or ache or shout.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>And trees are all this poem is about.</span></div>\n<span class=\"mandatory_credit_block\"><span class=\"mandatory_credit_line\">“Two Trees” from RAIN by Don Paterson. Copyright © 2009 by Don Paterson. Reprinted by permission of Farrar, Straus and Giroux.</span></span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">resentment of Don Miguel</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">unknown motives</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">sheer ignorance</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">ruthless greed</p>"],"answer":2}]